entry.title: Use ANGLE extension to skip texture renderability checks.
entry.content:
1. When a texture is created on GLES3 context and used/imported on GLES2

context, it could fail renderability validiation checks in ANGLE. This

is because texture could be created with a format in GLES3 context

which is invalid in GLES2 context.



Use ANGLE extension to set texture parameters using glTexParameteri to

skip ANGLE validation checks on that texture when it is used in GLES2

context.



This is used when we create texture in chrome in GLES3 context using

glTexStorage* which would result in using a sized format RGBA8 which is

not supported in GLES2 context resulting in ANGLE validation failures.



2. Enable gles3 with passthrough command decoder on Android.



3. Don't enable gles3 with passthrough on emulators for now.

entry.title: Replace manual fetch/XHR Attribution-Reporting headers with options
entry.content:
https://github.com/WICG/attribution-reporting-api/pull/757

https://github.com/WICG/attribution-reporting-api/pull/773



Previously, users of fetch and XHR opted in to Attribution Reporting by

manually setting the corresponding header. However, this was error-prone

and not precise, as the header could be set even when the browser would

reject registrations in the subsequent response, and required full

CORS support on the server. This change doesn't fully remove the CORS

requirements as a result of the responses still being processed in the

renderer.



We implement this by propagating the eligibility as a field on

ResourceRequest. The IDL, Mojo, and fetch/XHR changes are largely based

on the similar setup for Trust Tokens.



This also allow us to remove all related structured-header parsing

from //components/attribution_reporting, as the new ResourceRequest

field can be directly and far more efficiently inspected.



Moving this logic out of blink and content and into the network

service will make it easier to move all Attribution Reporting

response-handling there in the future, which is needed to address

crbug.com/1374121.

entry.title: Adds metrics to FLEDGE Latency UKM on GenerateBid dependency latency.
entry.content:
The GenerateBid flow executed in the BidderWorklet invokes the V8State's

GenerateBid only when all of the dependencies needed for that invocation

have been satisfied. In assessing the latency critical path of the

auction, particular attention should be paid to these convergence

points, where the delay in any one of these dependencies contributes

directly to the latency critical path. Because UKM doesn't allow us to

record repeated metrics (only repeated events), we're somewhat limited

in what data we can capture about the critical path. As such, in this

change, we add metrics that only record the time on the critical path

between the time that the last dependency was fulfilled and the time

that the second-to-last dependency was fulfilled. This still gives us a

sufficiently clear view of where to further invest optimization efforts.

entry.title: COOP: restrict-properties 4/*: proxy management.
entry.content:
This patch implements proxy management that supports cross-

BrowsingContext group communication. Proxy creation takes into account

the properties restrictions that will be applied, and only provide the

minimal number of proxies to support the valid use cases:

- Only the opener and openee are exposed across the BrowsingContextGroup

boundary.

- Proxies may be created on demand to support postMessage's

event.source.

- A minimal chain of ancestors for subframe proxies, required by the

way Chrome implements proxies.



This prevents XSLeaks by scanning proxies existence. Details are

available here:

https://docs.google.com/document/d/1TaC1gk_54B_hpBeIopqG4wgkTk1kZOha7I_P2nMRKSs/edit?usp=sharing&resourcekey=0-TiQk3dQsHngZMIsQOueDug



Proxy creation implies modifications mostly to RenderFrameHostManager,

while deletion is a simple change in BrowsingContextGroupSwap.



The rest of this patch makes sure that we are actually considering

proxies that might now exist across BrowsingInstances. In practice,

this is all the call sites of SiteInstance::IsRelatedSiteInstance().



In particular:

- postMessage should be permitted across BrowsingInstances in the same

CoopRelatedGroup.

- Navigation should not be permitted across BrowsingInstances.

- Closing windows should not be permitted across BrowsingInstances.

- Proxy can exist across BrowsingInstances, and the sanity check

planned in BrowsingContextState now needs to be about

CoopRelatedGroup.



New browser tests are added to verify the behaviors listed above. WPTs

are updated to reflect the current state of development: openers now

provide access to cross-origin properties (apart from some that are

validated by the browser, like window.close() and navigations). They

will be restricted to only window.closed and window.postMessage() in a

follow-up patch, by renderer-side checks.



Low-Coverage-Reason: BrowsingContextState new mode is unfinished

and untestable in conjunction with COOP. A disabled test was added with

a TODO to cover this code once the feature is implemented.

entry.title: Move cursor constraints from WebCursor to ui::Cursor
entry.content:
When creating a custom cursor, `content::WebCursor` places some limits

on its parameters. Namely, a maximum size in DIPs for the cursor image

and a lower bound on the scale factor so that the previous value

doesn't overflow. Additionally, the hotspot is always clamped to the

image dimensions.



In order to advance the removal of WebCursor, this CL moves these checks

to `ui::Cursor`. The hotspot will be clamped when building a custom

cursor, and the image size will be checked in a new static method

`AreDimensionsValidForWeb`, which will be used both by Blink and the

cursor mojom traits, so that even compromised renderers cannot bypass

these limits.

entry.title: [BSC]: Implement `BoundSessionRequestThrottledInRendererManager`
entry.content:
`BoundSessionRequestThrottledInRendererManager` is responsible for

notifying the browser that there are one or more requests blocked in the

renderer as it sees the required short lived cookie as expired.



On a follow-up CL, `BoundSessionRequestThrottledInRendererManager` will

be wrapped in `BoundSessionRequestThrottledListener` and passed to

`GoogleURLLoaderThrottler`. This allows the renderer to request a

refresh from the browser and allow it to resume requests on success ,

timeout or failure.



There is a single mojo pipe from the browser process to a renderer

process. `BoundSessionRequestThrottledListener` owns this pipe.

`GoogleURLLoaderThrottler` has one instance per network request and can

be created on different threads. Therefore calls to

`BoundSessionRequestThrottledListener` must be done one a single thread

`IO` thread.



Bug: b/263264391, 1392135

entry.title: [text-wrap-pretty] Fix `min-content` when `text-indent` is applied
entry.content:
This patch fixes `min-content` for `NGInlineNode` when

`text-indent` is applied. Before this patch, there were two

separate issues:

1. `HandleTextForFastMinContent` is an optimization for min-

and max-content by creating single item for the max-width

of all words in an `NGInlineItemResult`. The optimization

shouldn't apply when `text-indent` is applied, because the

first and following lines have different available widths.

2. When an instance of `NGLineBreaker` is reused multiple

times, it resets `is_first_formatted_line_` (and therefore

`text-indent`) only by `item_index`. This patch fixes it to
